newsitem.title: USA: U.S. cash soymeal - Rail offers slip pre-holiday.
newsitem.headline: U.S. cash soymeal - Rail offers slip pre-holiday.

text.p: Offers for soymeal in rail markets were mostly lower Monday in response to a slowdown in demand in front of the U.S. Thanksgiving holiday, brokers said.
"There's not much trade right now and most of the interest is in December positions," a river dealer said.
Despite the lower rail offers, the soymeal supply scenario was expected to remain tight and demand was expected to remain good through December, cash sources said.
"I'm looking for a slow week, but I'm not looking for the board (CBOT futures) to break," one Minnesota dealer said.
Interest in the spot market will be dampened as long as the market is trading at an inverse, other dealers said.
"There's nothing trading right now," one dealer said. "Right now everybody's hesitant with the inverse in the market."
The National Oilseed Processors Association put the weekly crush Friday at 29.68 million bushels. That figure came in at the low end of trade expectations for 29.5 million to 30.6 million bushels.
Down time at some of the crushing plants caused the recently high crush pace to wane somewhat.
